verdict.reasoning:
Code confirmed exactly as described. public/index.html lines 88-105:

```
let joining = false;
...
async function attemptJoin(code) {
  ...
  if (joining) return;
  joining = true;
  lastAttempt = code;
  errEl.textContent = '';
  try {
    await api('GET', `/api/join/${code}`);
    location.href = `/vote.html?code=${code}`;
  } catch {
    errEl.textContent = t('landing.join.errNotFound');
    joining = false;
  }
}
```

`joining` is reset to false only in the catch branch. On the success path it stays true forever because the code relies on `location.href` triggering a full navigation/reload that would normally discard all JS state — but that assumption breaks under bfcache restoration.

Verified no mitigation exists anywhere in the codebase: grepped public/index.html and public/common.js for `pageshow`, `beforeunload`, `visibilitychange`, `persisted`, `unload` — zero matches. No listener resets `joining` on back/forward navigation.

Verified bfcache eligibility is not blocked by response headers: server.js serves static HTML with `Cache-Control: no-cache` (not `no-store`), and vercel.json sets no cache-control header on static assets at all. `no-store` is what disqualifies a page from Chrome's bfcache; `no-cache` does not. index.html also opens no SSE/WebSocket connections itself (those are only opened in presenter.html/vote.html), so it has no other obvious bfcache-disqualifying activity. This makes index.html a strong bfcache candidate in Safari (notoriously aggressive) and modern Chrome/Firefox.

Consequence when triggered: after a successful join+redirect, pressing back restores index.html with `joining` permanently `true`. Every subsequent join attempt — whether via submit button or the auto-submit-on-6-digits path (line 116-117) — silently no-ops at the `if (joining) return;` guard with zero error feedback, since that guard runs before the length/error-message logic has a chance to update the UI. This is a real, logically-sound defect that would look like the app being simply broken to an audience member.

Downgrading severity from critical to high: this is a genuine, unrecovered-state bug affecting a primary flow with no user-facing error (bad for a demo), but it is not data-loss, not a security issue, and has a simple recovery path (a full page reload/refresh, or closing and reopening the tab, resets the JS state since only bfcache-restore preserves it). "Critical" is generally reserved for data corruption/security/total-outage-with-no-workaround; this is better characterized as a high-severity UX/functional bug given the plausible-but-not-universal trigger condition and the existence of an easy (if non-obvious to end users) recovery.

Code confirms the report exactly. In public/presenter.html, the delete-option handler (line 692-701) contains:

```js
row.querySelector('button').addEventListener('click', () => {
  s.options.splice(i, 1);
  // Quiz: „richtige Antwort" der verschobenen/gelöschten Option nachführen
  if (s.type === 'quiz' && Number.isInteger(s.correct)) {
    if (s.correct === i) s.correct = 0;   // <-- line 696: silent fallback
    else if (s.correct > i) s.correct -= 1;
  }
  renderOptionRows();
  scheduleSave();
});
```

When the option currently marked correct (`s.correct === i`) is deleted, `s.correct` is silently reset to 0 (option 1) with no confirm(), alert(), or any in-app dialog (the app does have a `confirmDialog()` helper used elsewhere, e.g. line 715, but it is NOT invoked here). `renderOptionRows()` then calls `refreshQuizCorrect()` (line 705), which regenerates the `<select>` and marks index 0 as `selected` (line 671-674) — visually indistinguishable from a deliberate choice, so a presenter has no cue that the correct answer changed.

`scheduleSave()` persists this immediately (no explicit "Save" step to catch/undo it).

Downstream impact is verified as claimed:
- `lib/domain.mjs` line 300-303: live voting compares each participant's choice against `slide.correct` to award quiz points — so a silently-wrong `correct` value mis-scores every participant's answer during a live quiz.
- `lib/domain.mjs` line 204: `computeResults()` returns `correct: slide.correct` which flows into the editor's results panel and exports.
- `lib/domain.mjs` line 748: XLSX export marks the '✓' column based on `results.correct`.
- `public/pptx-export.js` line 248: `addQuiz` highlights `i === res.correct` in green in the exported PPTX.
- Server-side `sanitizeSlide` (lib/domain.mjs line 66-67) has the same "fall back to 0 with no signal" pattern, so even a full round-trip through the server doesn't add a safety net.

This is a real, unmitigated silent-data-corruption bug: editing quiz options can flip the "correct" answer to a different, wrong option with zero warning, and that wrong value then drives live scoring, the editor's result view, and both XLSX/PPTX exports. For an investor demo this is exactly the kind of thing that could make a quiz score answers incorrectly on stage or export a slide with the wrong answer highlighted — a credible, embarrassing, silent-correctness bug. The reported "high" severity is appropriate (not a crash, but a silent-wrong-answer / data-integrity issue with direct live-scoring and export consequences), so no correction needed.

Verified directly in public/presenter.html. Lines 950-953 (btnResetSlide) and 954-957 (btnResetAll) both call `await api('POST', .../reset, ...)` with zero try/catch:

```
$('btnResetSlide').addEventListener('click', async () => {
  if (!await confirmDialog({...})) return;
  await api('POST', `/api/presentations/${PRES_ID}/reset`, { slideId: currentSlide().id }, TOKEN);
});
$('btnResetAll').addEventListener('click', async () => {
  if (!await confirmDialog({...})) return;
  await api('POST', `/api/presentations/${PRES_ID}/reset`, {}, TOKEN);
});
```

Confirmed `api()` in public/common.js throws an Error on any network failure or non-ok HTTP response (lines 21-36), so a rejected promise is guaranteed on failure. Confirmed there is no global `unhandledrejection`/`window.onerror` handler anywhere in public/*.js or public/*.html that would surface this to the user. Confirmed the overflow-menu wrapper (function overflowMenu, line 329) does not catch errors either — it just calls `it.onClick()` synchronously, which for the reset entries (line 924, and header menu line 968) simply re-dispatches a `.click()` on the same unguarded buttons.

For direct comparison, btnArchive's handler (lines 841-847) performs the same kind of destructive POST but wraps it in try/catch and shows `alertDialog(...)` on failure, then calls `load()` to resync state on success — confirming these two reset handlers are indeed outliers with zero error handling, exactly as reported.

Impact: if the reset POST fails (auth/token issue, network blip, server error) during a live demo, the user sees the confirm dialog close with no follow-up feedback whatsoever — no error message, no re-sync, no indication the action didn't happen — and may believe stale results were cleared when they were not. This is a real, verifiable gap and plausible to be embarrassing in an investor demo (presenter resets between segments, believes it worked, old numbers reappear). The severity of 'high' given by the reviewer is appropriate: it's not a crash, but it is the only two destructive/irreversible-feeling actions in the whole file with absolutely no failure feedback, unlike every comparable POST call including the directly analogous 'Archive' action.

Verified against the actual code, the bug is real and reproducible with normal usage (not a contrived edge case).

public/app.css:390-392:
```
.bar-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: minmax(90px, 200px) 1fr 80px; gap: 0.8rem; align-items: center; }
.bar-label { font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--grey-6); overflow-wrap: anywhere; }
```
No line-clamp, no max-height, no title/tooltip fallback. `align-items: center` (default grid cross-axis alignment) is never overridden for `.bar-row`, so `.bar-track` (fixed height, clamp 2.4rem–3.4rem in present mode) and `.bar-value` (single-line, `white-space: nowrap`) are vertically centered against whatever height the wrapped label produces.

In present mode the problem is amplified, not mitigated: `.present-results .bar-label { font-size: clamp(1.1rem, 1.8vw, 1.6rem); }` (app.css:407) grows the label font up to 25.6px while the label column stays capped at 200px (`minmax(90px, 200px)` is unchanged by the present-mode rules). At ~25px font size, ~200px width yields roughly 14-15 characters per line.

Crucially, long labels are not a hypothetical: option text is capped at exactly 120 characters both client-side (`public/presenter.html:684` `maxlength="120"`) and server-side (`lib/domain.mjs` `clampText(String(o), 120)` for `choice`/`ranking`/`points`/`quiz`). A 120-char option (a full-sentence answer, which is common in real feedback surveys) at ~14 chars/line would wrap to 8+ lines, producing exactly the "floating bar in a sea of whitespace" effect described, right next to a short one-line "Gut" row rendered compactly. `public/common.js` (lines 238-243, 268-277, 316-319) confirms `.bar-label` is populated with raw `esc(option)` text with no truncation or tooltip.

This is a legitimate, easily-triggered visual defect in the main results chart shown during live presentation — plausible to occur unintentionally in a real demo whenever a presenter or attendee enters a longer, natural-language option. Severity "high" is appropriate: it's confined to visual/readability polish (no data loss or functional break), which keeps it out of "critical", but it directly affects the primary result-visualization surface an audience watches during an investor demo, matching the reporter's assessment.
